					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Bra=
nch of elementary mathematics</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For the 2004=
 song by Brooke Fraser, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithm=
etic_(song)" title=3D"Arithmetic (song)">Arithmetic (song)</a>. For the 170=
3 Russian textbook, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic=
_(book)" title=3D"Arithmetic (book)"><i>Arithmetic</i> (book)</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Arithmetic_operations.svg" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img alt=3D"Diagram of symbols of arithmetic operations" src=3D=
"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/Arithmetic_opera=
tions.svg/250px-Arithmetic_operations.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"=
250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-=
file-height=3D"512"></a><figcaption>The main arithmetic operations are addi=
tion, subtraction, multiplication, and division.</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Arithmetic</b> is an elementary branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a> that deals=
 with numerical operations like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ad=
dition" title=3D"Addition">addition</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Subtraction" title=3D"Subtraction">subtraction</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication" title=3D"Multiplication">multiplic=
ation</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(mathemati=
cs)" title=3D"Division (mathematics)">division</a>. In a wider sense, it al=
so includes <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation" title=
=3D"Exponentiation">exponentiation</a>, extraction of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nth_root" title=3D"Nth root">roots</a>, and taking <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithms" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Logarithms">logarithms</a>.
</p><p>Arithmetic systems can be distinguished based on the type of numbers=
 they operate on. Integer arithmetic is about calculations with positive an=
d negative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integ=
er">integers</a>. Rational number arithmetic involves operations on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction" title=3D"Fraction">fractions</a=
> of integers. Real number arithmetic is about calculations with <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real numb=
ers</a>, which include both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ration=
al_number" title=3D"Rational number">rational</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_number" title=3D"Irrational number">irration=
al numbers</a>.
</p><p>Another distinction is based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Numeral_system" title=3D"Numeral system">numeral system</a> employ=
ed to perform calculations. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decima=
l" title=3D"Decimal">Decimal</a> arithmetic is the most common. It uses the=
 basic numerals from 0 to 9 and their combinations to express <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number" title=3D"Number">numbers</a>. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number" title=3D"Binary number">Bi=
nary</a> arithmetic, by contrast, is used by most computers and represents =
numbers as combinations of the basic numerals 0 and 1. <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_arithmetic" title=3D"Computer arithmetic">Com=
puter arithmetic</a> deals with the specificities of the implementation of =
binary arithmetic on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" tit=
le=3D"Computer">computers</a>. Some arithmetic systems operate on <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_object" title=3D"Mathematica=
l object">mathematical objects</a> other than numbers, such as <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_arithmetic" title=3D"Interval arithme=
tic">interval arithmetic</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
atrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrix</a> arithmetic.
</p><p>Arithmetic operations form the basis of many branches of mathematics=
, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebr=
a">algebra</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D=
"Calculus">calculus</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stati=
stics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>. They play a similar role in the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sciences" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Sciences">sciences</a>, like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics">economics</a>. Arithmetic is pre=
sent in many aspects of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daily_life=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Daily life">daily life</a>, for example, t=
o calculate change while shopping or to manage <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Personal_finances" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Personal fin=
ances">personal finances</a>. It is one of the earliest forms of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_education" title=3D"Mathematics =
education">mathematics education</a> that students encounter. Its cognitive=
 and conceptual foundations are studied by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Psychology" title=3D"Psychology">psychology</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy" title=3D"Philosophy">philosophy</a>.
</p><p>The practice of arithmetic is at least thousands and possibly tens o=
f thousands of years old. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_=
civilizations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient civilizations">Ancien=
t civilizations</a> like the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancie=
nt_Egypt" title=3D"Ancient Egypt">Egyptians</a> and the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sumer" title=3D"Sumer">Sumerians</a> invented numeral=
 systems to solve practical arithmetic problems in about 3000 BCE. Starting=
 in the 7th and 6th centuries BCE, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Ancient_Greeks" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient Greeks">ancient=
 Greeks</a> initiated a more abstract study of numbers and introduced the m=
ethod of rigorous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_pro=
of" title=3D"Mathematical proof">mathematical proofs</a>. The <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_India" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"A=
ncient India">ancient Indians</a> developed the concept of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Zero">zero</a=
> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu%E2%80%93Arabic_num=
eral_system" title=3D"Hindu=E2=80=93Arabic numeral system">decimal system</=
a>, which Arab mathematicians further refined and spread to the Western wor=
ld during the medieval period. The first <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mechanical_calculator" title=3D"Mechanical calculator">mechanical ca=
lculators</a> were invented in the 17th century. The 18th and 19th centurie=
s saw the development of modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nu=
mber_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number theory</a> and the formulation =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiomatic_system" title=3D"Axio=
matic system">axiomatic foundations</a> of arithmetic. In the 20th century,=
 the emergence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_calcu=
lator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electronic calculator">electronic cal=
culators</a> and computers revolutionized the accuracy and speed with which=
 arithmetic calculations could be performed.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition,_etymology,_and_=
related_fields"><span id=3D"Definition.2C_etymology.2C_and_related_fields">=
</span>Definition, etymology, and related fields</h2><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;secti=
on=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition, etymology, and related fields"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>Arithmetic is the fundamental branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a> that studies nu=
mbers and their operations. In particular, it deals with numerical calculat=
ions using the arithmetic operations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">addition</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Subtraction" title=3D"Subtraction">subtraction</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication" title=3D"Multiplication">=
multiplication</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(=
mathematics)" title=3D"Division (mathematics)">division</a>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithm=
etic#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In a wider sense, it also includes <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation" title=3D"Exponentiation">expo=
nentiation</a>, extraction of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nth_=
root" title=3D"Nth root">roots</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithm</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite=
_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> The term <i>arithmetic</i> has its root in the Latin te=
rm <i lang=3D"la"><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/arithmetica#Lat=
in" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:arithmetica">arithmetica</a></i> which de=
rives from the Ancient Greek words <span lang=3D"grc"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E1%BC%80%CF%81%CE%B9%CE%B8%CE%BC%CF%8C%CF%82#Ancient_=
Greek" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:=E1=BC=80=CF=81=CE=B9=CE=B8=CE=BC=CF=
=8C=CF=82">=E1=BC=80=CF=81=CE=B9=CE=B8=CE=BC=CF=8C=CF=82</a></span> (<i>ari=
thmos</i>), meaning <span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss=
-text">number</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span>, and <span lang=3D"=
grc"><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E1%BC%80%CF%81%CE%B9%CE%B8%=
CE%BC%CE%B7%CF%84%CE%B9%CE%BA%CE%AE#Ancient_Greek" class=3D"extiw" title=3D=
"wikt:=E1=BC=80=CF=81=CE=B9=CE=B8=CE=BC=CE=B7=CF=84=CE=B9=CE=BA=CE=AE">=E1=
=BC=80=CF=81=CE=B9=CE=B8=CE=BC=CE=B7=CF=84=CE=B9=CE=BA=CE=AE</a></span> <sp=
an lang=3D"grc"><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%CF%84%CE%AD%CF%8=
7%CE%BD%CE%B7#Ancient_Greek" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:=CF=84=CE=AD=CF=
=87=CE=BD=CE=B7">=CF=84=CE=AD=CF=87=CE=BD=CE=B7</a></span> (<i>arithmetike =
tekhne</i>), meaning <span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"glos=
s-text">the art of counting</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Arithmetic#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>There are disagreements about its precise definition. According to a=
 narrow characterization, arithmetic deals only with <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Natural =
numbers">natural numbers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
However, the more common view is to include operations on <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integers">=
integers</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_numbers" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rational numbers">rational numbers</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Real numbers">real numbers</a>, and sometimes also <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Compl=
ex numbers">complex numbers</a> in its scope.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_not=
e-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Some definitions restrict arithmetic to the field of numeri=
cal calculations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When understoo=
d in a wider sense, it also includes the study of how the concept of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Numbers">numbers</a> developed, the analysis of properties of and relations=
 between numbers, and the examination of the axiomatic structure of arithme=
tic operations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
