<p>Integer arithmetic is the branch of arithmetic that deals with the manip=
ulation of positive and negative whole numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_no=
te-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Simple one-digit operations can be performed by followin=
g or memorizing a table that presents the results of all possible combinati=
ons, like an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addition_table" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Addition table">addition table</a> or a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication_table" title=3D"Multiplica=
tion table">multiplication table</a>. Other common methods are verbal <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counting" title=3D"Counting">counting</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finger-counting" title=3D"F=
inger-counting">finger-counting</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-69"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
