<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Number_theory">Number theor=
y</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Number theory">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=
=3D"Number theory">Number theory</a></div>
<p>Number theory studies the structure and properties of integers as well a=
s the relations and laws between them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-85" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-85"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Some of the main branches of modern number theory include <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_number_theory" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Elementary number theory">elementary number theory</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_number_theory" title=3D"Anal=
ytic number theory">analytic number theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Algebraic_number_theory" title=3D"Algebraic number theory">al=
gebraic number theory</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geo=
metric_number_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geometric number theor=
y">geometric number theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-86" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-86"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Elementary number theory studies aspects of integers that can be investi=
gated using elementary methods. Its topics include <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Divisibility" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Divisibility"=
>divisibility</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorization" =
title=3D"Factorization">factorization</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Primality" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Primality">primality=
</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Analytic number theory,=
 by contrast, relies on techniques from analysis and calculus. It examines =
problems like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number_theorem=
" title=3D"Prime number theorem">how prime numbers are distributed</a> and =
the claim that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjec=
ture" title=3D"Goldbach's conjecture">every even number is a sum of two pri=
me numbers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-88" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-88"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Algebraic num=
ber theory employs algebraic structures to analyze the properties of and re=
lations between numbers. Examples are the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)" title=3D"Field (mathematics)">fields</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D=
"Ring (mathematics)">rings</a>, as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Algebraic_number_field" title=3D"Algebraic number field">algebraic numb=
er fields</a> like the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_of_int=
egers" title=3D"Ring of integers">ring of integers</a>. Geometric number th=
eory uses concepts from geometry to study numbers. For instance, it investi=
gates how lattice points with integer coordinates behave in a plane.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-89" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Arithmetic#cite_note-89"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Further branches of number theory a=
re <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabilistic_number_theory" ti=
tle=3D"Probabilistic number theory">probabilistic number theory</a>, which =
employs methods from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_t=
heory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability theory</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-90" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithm=
etic#cite_note-90"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Com=
binatorial_number_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Combinatorial numb=
er theory">combinatorial number theory</a>, which relies on the field of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorics" title=3D"Combinatoric=
s">combinatorics</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-91" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-91"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_number_theory" title=3D"Com=
putational number theory">computational number theory</a>, which approaches=
 number-theoretic problems with computational methods,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9=
2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#=
cite_note-92"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> and applied number theory, which examines the app=
lication of number theory to fields like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Biology" title=3D"Biology">biology</a>, and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptography" title=3D"Cryptography">cryptography</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-93" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Influential theorems in number theory include the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic" title=3D"Fundamen=
tal theorem of arithmetic">fundamental theorem of arithmetic</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_theorem" title=3D"Euclid's the=
orem">Euclid's theorem</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fe=
rmat%27s_Last_Theorem" title=3D"Fermat's Last Theorem">Fermat's Last Theore=
m</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-94" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-94"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> According to the funda=
mental theorem of arithmetic, every integer greater than 1 is either a prim=
e number or can be represented as a unique product of prime numbers. For ex=
ample, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_18" class=3D"mw-=
