></sup> In cases where absolute precision is not required, the problem of c=
alculating arithmetic operations on real numbers is usually addressed by <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truncation" title=3D"Truncation">tru=
ncation</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding" title=3D"=
Rounding">rounding</a>. For truncation, a certain number of leftmost digits=
 are kept and remaining digits are discarded or replaced by zeros. For exam=
ple, the number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
=CF=80</span> has an infinite number of digits starting with 3.14159.... If=
 this number is truncated to 4 decimal places, the result is 3.141. Roundin=
g is a similar process in which the last preserved digit is increased by on=
e if the next digit is 5 or greater but remains the same if the next digit =
is less than 5, so that the rounded number is the best approximation of a g=
iven precision for the original number. For instance, if the number <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> is rounded=
 to 4 decimal places, the result is 3.142 because the following digit is a =
5, so 3.142 is closer to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">=CF=80</span> than 3.141.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-112" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-112"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>107<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> These methods allow computers to efficiently perform approximate ca=
lculations on real numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-113" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-113"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>108<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Approximations_and_errors">=
Approximations and errors</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit =
section: Approximations and errors"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In science and engineering, numbers represent estimates of physical quan=
tities derived from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measurement" t=
itle=3D"Measurement">measurement</a> or modeling. Unlike mathematically exa=
ct numbers such as <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">=CF=80</span> or <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<=
span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xml=
ns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\sqrt =
{2}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\sqrt {2}}}<=
/annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b4afc1e27d418021bf10898eb44a7f5f315735ff" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:3.098ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\s=
qrt {2}}}"></span>=E2=81=A0</span>,</span> scientifically relevant numerica=
l data are inherently inexact, involving some <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Measurement_uncertainty" title=3D"Measurement uncertainty">meas=
urement uncertainty</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-114" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-114"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>109<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> O=
ne basic way to express the degree of certainty about each number's value a=
nd avoid <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/False_precision" title=3D=
"False precision">false precision</a> is to round each measurement to a cer=
tain number of digits, called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign=
ificant_digit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Significant digit">significan=
t digits</a>, which are implied to be accurate. For example, a person's hei=
ght measured with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tape_measure" =
title=3D"Tape measure">tape measure</a> might only be precisely known to th=
e nearest centimeter, so should be presented as 1.62 meters rather than 1.6=
217 meters. If converted to imperial units, this quantity should be rounded=
 to 64 inches or 63.8 inches rather than 63.7795 inches, to clearly convey =
the precision of the measurement. When a number is written using ordinary d=
ecimal notation, leading zeros are not significant, and trailing zeros of n=
umbers not written with a decimal point are implicitly considered to be non=
-significant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-115" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-115"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>110<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example,=
 the numbers 0.056 and 1200 each have only 2 significant digits, but the nu=
mber 40.00 has 4 significant digits. Representing uncertainty using only si=
gnificant digits is a relatively crude method, with some unintuitive subtle=
ties; explicitly keeping track of an estimate or upper bound of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Approximation_error" title=3D"Approximati=
on error">approximation error</a> is a more sophisticated approach.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-116" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Arithmetic#cite_note-116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>111<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the example, the person's hei=
ght might be represented as <span class=3D"nowrap">1.62 =C2=B1 0.005</span>=
 meters or <span class=3D"nowrap">63.8 =C2=B1 0.2 inches</span>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-117" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Arithmetic#cite_note-117"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>112<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In performing calculations with uncertain quantities, the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propagation_of_uncertainty" title=3D"Propaga=
tion of uncertainty">uncertainty should be propagated</a> to calculated qua=
ntities. When adding or subtracting two or more quantities, add the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_uncertainty" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Absolute uncertainty">absolute uncertainties</a> of each summan=
d together to obtain the absolute uncertainty of the sum. When multiplying =
or dividing two or more quantities, add the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Relative_uncertainty" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Relative unc=
ertainty">relative uncertainties</a> of each factor together to obtain the =
relative uncertainty of the product.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-118" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-118"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>113<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> When representing uncertainty by significant digits, uncertainty=
 can be coarsely propagated by rounding the result of adding or subtracting=
 two or more quantities to the leftmost last significant decimal place amon=
g the summands, and by rounding the result of multiplying or dividing two o=
r more quantities to the least number of significant digits among the facto=
rs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-119" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-119"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>114<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (See <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#Arithmetic" title=3D"Significan=
t figures">Significant figures =C2=A7&nbsp;Arithmetic</a>.)
</p><p>More sophisticated methods of dealing with uncertain values include =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_arithmetic" title=3D"Inte=
rval arithmetic">interval arithmetic</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Affine_arithmetic" title=3D"Affine arithmetic">affine arithmetic=
</a>. Interval arithmetic describes operations on <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)" title=3D"Interval (mathematics)">in=
tervals</a>. Intervals can be used to represent a range of values if one do=
es not know the precise magnitude, for example, because of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measurement_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Measurement error">measurement errors</a>. Interval arithmetic includes ope=
rations like addition and multiplication on intervals, as in <span class=3D=
"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-i=
nline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://=
