ref-123" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arith=
metic#cite_note-123"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>118<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A common method employed by computers to approximate real number ari=
thmetic is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating-point_a=
rithmetic" title=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">floating-point arithmetic</a=
>. It represents real numbers similar to the scientific notation through th=
ree numbers: a significand, a base, and an exponent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-124=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#c=
ite_note-124"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>119<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> The precision of the significand is limited by t=
he number of bits allocated to represent it. If an arithmetic operation res=
ults in a number that requires more bits than are available, the computer r=
ounds the result to the closest representable number. This leads to <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Rounding error">rounding errors</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-125" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-1=
25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>120<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> A consequence of this behavior is that certain laws of ari=
thmetic are violated by floating-point arithmetic. For example, floating-po=
int addition is not associative since the rounding errors introduced can de=
pend on the order of the additions. This means that the result of <span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mat=
hml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"ht=
tp://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (a+b)+c}">
