cite-bracket">[</span>121<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
e most common technical standard used for floating-point arithmetic is call=
ed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_754" title=3D"IEEE 754">IE=
EE 754</a>. Among other things, it determines how numbers are represented, =
how arithmetic operations and rounding are performed, and how errors and ex=
ceptions are handled.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-127" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-127"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>122<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In=
 cases where computation speed is not a limiting factor, it is possible to =
use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arbitrary-precision_arithmetic=
" title=3D"Arbitrary-precision arithmetic">arbitrary-precision arithmetic</=
a>, for which the precision of calculations is only restricted by the compu=
ter's memory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-128" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-128"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>123<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Tool_use">Tool use</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Tool use"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mental_calculation_at_primary=
_school.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"Painting of students=
 engaged in mental arithmetic" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedi=
a/commons/thumb/9/9c/Mental_calculation_at_primary_school.jpg/250px-Mental_=
calculation_at_primary_school.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"187" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1283" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"958"></a><figcaption>Calculations in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mental_arithmetic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mental arithmetic=
">mental arithmetic</a> are done exclusively in the mind without relying on=
 external aids.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Forms of arithmetic can also be distinguished by the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_instrument" title=3D"Mathematical instru=
ment">tools</a> employed to perform calculations and include many approache=
s besides the regular use of pen and paper. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mental_arithmetic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mental arithmet=
ic">Mental arithmetic</a> relies exclusively on the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mind" title=3D"Mind">mind</a> without external tools. Ins=
tead, it utilizes visualization, memorization, and certain calculation tech=
niques to solve arithmetic problems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-129" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-129"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>124<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> One such technique is the compensation method, which consists in=
 altering the numbers to make the calculation easier and then adjusting the=
 result afterward. For example, instead of calculating <span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline =
mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3=
.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 85-47}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>85</mn>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mn>47</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 85-47}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ec30b07610091908d287f893e38106bb7c43f4f3" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:7.49ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 85-4=
7}"></span>, one calculates <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-elemen=
t-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=
=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" altt=
ext=3D"{\displaystyle 85-50}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>85</mn>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mn>50</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 85-50}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f7f4d95ffe22c444668749bcf4950e8907aad42b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:7.49ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 85-5=
0}"></span> which is easier because it uses a round number. In the next ste=
p, one adds <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
e;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\display=
style 3}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>3</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 3}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/991e33c6e207b12546f15bdfee8b5726eafbbb2f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.162ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 3}"=
></span> to the result to compensate for the earlier adjustment.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-130" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Arithmetic#cite_note-130"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>125<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Mental arithmetic is often taught in=
 primary education to train the numerical abilities of the students.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-131" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Arithmetic#cite_note-131"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>126<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The human body can also be employed as an arithmetic tool. The use o=
f hands in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finger_counting" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Finger counting">finger counting</a> is often int=
roduced to young children to teach them numbers and simple calculations. In=
 its most basic form, the number of extended fingers corresponds to the rep=
resented quantity and arithmetic operations like addition and subtraction a=
re performed by extending or retracting fingers. This system is limited to =
small numbers compared to more advanced systems which employ different appr=
oaches to represent larger quantities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-132" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-132">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>127<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> The human voice is used as an arithmetic aid in verbal countin=
g.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-133" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-133"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>128<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Chinese-abacus.jpg" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img alt=3D"Photo of a Chinese abacus" src=3D"https://u=
pload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Chinese-abacus.jpg/250px-C=
hinese-abacus.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"164" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2588" data-file-height=3D"1700"></a><f=
igcaption>Abacuses are tools to perform arithmetic operations by moving bea=
ds.</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tally_marks" title=3D"Tally mar=
ks">Tally marks</a> are a simple system based on external tools other than =
the body. This system relies on mark making, such as strokes drawn on a sur=
face or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Notch_(engineering)" title=
=3D"Notch (engineering)">notches</a> carved into a wooden stick, to keep tr=
ack of quantities. Some forms of tally marks arrange the strokes in groups =
of five to make them easier to read.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-134" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-134"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abacus" title=3D"Abacus=
">abacus</a> is a more advanced tool to represent numbers and perform calcu=
lations. An abacus usually consists of a series of rods, each holding sever=
al <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bead" title=3D"Bead">beads</a>.=
 Each bead represents a quantity, which is counted if the bead is moved fro=
m one end of a rod to the other. Calculations happen by manipulating the po=
sitions of beads until the final bead pattern reveals the result.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-135" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Arithmetic#cite_note-135"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>130<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Related aids include <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counting_board" title=3D"Counting board">countin=
g boards</a>, which use tokens whose value depends on the area on the board=
 in which they are placed,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-136" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-136"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counting_rods" title=3D"Coun=
ting rods">counting rods</a>, which are arranged in horizontal and vertical=
 patterns to represent different numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-137" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-13=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>132<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-139" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-139"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>f<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sector_(instrument)" title=
=3D"Sector (instrument)">Sectors</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Slide_rule" title=3D"Slide rule">slide rules</a> are more refined ca=
lculating instruments that rely on geometric relationships between differen=
t scales to perform both basic and advanced arithmetic operations.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-140" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Arithmetic#cite_note-140"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>134<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-142" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-1=
42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>g<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> Printed tables were particularly relevant as an aid to look =
up the results of operations like logarithm and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Trigonometry" title=3D"Trigonometry">trigonometric functions<=
/a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-143" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-143"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>136<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanical_calculator" titl=
e=3D"Mechanical calculator">Mechanical calculators</a> automate manual calc=
ulation processes. They present the user with some form of input device to =
enter numbers by turning dials or pressing keys. They include an internal m=
echanism usually consisting of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gea=
r" title=3D"Gear">gears</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lever=
" title=3D"Lever">levers</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Wheel" title=3D"Wheel">wheels</a> to perform calculations and display the r=
esults.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-144" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-144"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>137<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_calculator" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Electronic calculator">electronic calculators</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" title=3D"Computer">computers</a>, this =
procedure is further refined by replacing the mechanical components with <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_circuits" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Electronic circuits">electronic circuits</a> like <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microprocessor" title=3D"Microprocessor">=
microprocessors</a> that combine and transform electric signals to perform =
calculations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-145" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-145"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>138<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Others">Others</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Others"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Clock_group.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description=
"><img alt=3D"Diagram of modular arithmetic using a clock" src=3D"https://u=
pload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Clock_group.svg/250px-Cloc=
k_group.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"109" class=3D"m=
w-file-element" data-file-width=3D"560" data-file-height=3D"245"></a><figca=
ption>Example of modular arithmetic using a clock: after adding 4 hours to =
9 o'clock, the hand starts at the beginning again and points at 1 o'clock.<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>There are many other types of arithmetic. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Modular_arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">Modular arithme=
tic</a> operates on a finite set of numbers. If an operation would result i=
n a number outside this finite set then the number is adjusted back into th=
e set, similar to how the hands of clocks start at the beginning again afte=
r having completed one cycle. The number at which this adjustment happens i=
s called the modulus. For example, a regular clock has a modulus of 12. In =
the case of adding 4 to 9, this means that the result is not 13 but 1. The =
same principle applies also to other operations, such as subtraction, multi=
plication, and division.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-146" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-146"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>139<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some forms of arithmetic deal with operations performed on mathemati=
cal objects other than numbers. Interval arithmetic describes operations on=
 intervals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-147" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-147"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>140<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Vector arithme=
tic and matrix arithmetic describe arithmetic operations on <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_(mathematics_and_physics)" title=3D"Vector=
 (mathematics and physics)">vectors</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrices</a>=
, like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_addition" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Vector addition">vector addition</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_multiplication" title=3D"Matrix multipli=
cation">matrix multiplication</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-148" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-148"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>141<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>Arithmetic systems can be classified based on the numeral system the=
y rely on. For instance, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal" =
title=3D"Decimal">decimal</a> arithmetic describes arithmetic operations in=
 the decimal system. Other examples are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Binary_number" title=3D"Binary number">binary</a> arithmetic, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal" title=3D"Octal">octal</a> arithmet=
ic, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexadecimal" title=3D"Hexa=
decimal">hexadecimal</a> arithmetic.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-149" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-149"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>142<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>Compound unit arithmetic describes arithmetic operations performed o=
n magnitudes with compound units. It involves additional operations to gove=
rn the transformation between single unit and compound unit quantities. For=
 example, the operation of reduction is used to transform the compound quan=
tity 1 h 90 min into the single unit quantity 150 min.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic=
#cite_note-150"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>143<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Non-Diophantine arithmetics are arithmetic systems that violate trad=
itional arithmetic intuitions and include equations like <span class=3D"mwe=
-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inlin=
e mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.=
w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 1+1=3D1}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 1+1=3D1}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5120dbef0aa4b1760be59a33516661780dfc7a14" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:9.426ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 1+1=
=3D1}"></span> and <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"=
><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displ=
ay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\=
displaystyle 2+2=3D5}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>5</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 2+2=3D5}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/de4520e2da0b35c4bf907b9d6b933fb015ea0e52" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:9.426ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 2+2=
