<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Axiomatic_foundations">Axio=
matic foundations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DArithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Axiomatic foundations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiomatic_system" title=3D"Axio=
matic system">Axiomatic foundations</a> of arithmetic try to provide a smal=
l set of laws, called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" title=
=3D"Axiom">axioms</a>, from which all fundamental properties of and operati=
ons on numbers can be derived. They constitute logically consistent and sys=
tematic frameworks that can be used to formulate <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title=3D"Mathematical proof">mathematica=
l proofs</a> in a rigorous manner. Two well-known approaches are the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dedekind%E2%80%93Peano_axioms" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Dedekind=E2=80=93Peano axioms">Dedekind=E2=80=93Peano=
 axioms</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set-theoretic" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Set-theoretic">set-theoretic</a> constructions.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-153" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-153"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Dedekind=E2=80=93Peano axioms provide an axiomatization of the a=
rithmetic of natural numbers. Their basic principles were first formulated =
by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Dedekind" title=3D"Rich=
ard Dedekind">Richard Dedekind</a> and later refined by <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giuseppe_Peano" title=3D"Giuseppe Peano">Giuseppe Pea=
no</a>. They rely only on a small number of primitive mathematical concepts=
, such as 0, natural number, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
uccessor_function" title=3D"Successor function">successor</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-154" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ar=
ithmetic#cite_note-154"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>h<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Peano axioms determine how these c=
oncepts are related to each other. All other arithmetic concepts can then b=
e defined in terms of these primitive concepts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-155" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_n=
ote-155"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>147<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>0 is a natural number.</li>
<li>For every natural number, there is a successor, which is also a natural=
 number.</li>
<li>The successors of two different natural numbers are never identical.</l=
i>
<li>0 is not the successor of a natural number.</li>
<li>If a set contains 0 and every successor then it contains every natural =
number.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-156" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-156"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>148<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-158" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmet=
ic#cite_note-158"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>i<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Numbers greater than 0 are expressed by repeated application of the succ=
essor function <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: =
