class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ishango_bone_(cropped).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img alt=3D"Photo of the Ishango bone" src=3D"https://upload.w=
ikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Ishango_bone_%28cropped%29.jpg/25=
0px-Ishango_bone_%28cropped%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"150" height=
=3D"207" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"891" data-file-height=
=3D"1230"></a><figcaption>Some historians interpret the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ishango_bone" title=3D"Ishango bone">Ishango bone</a>=
 as one of the earliest arithmetic artifacts.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The earliest forms of arithmetic are sometimes traced back to <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counting" title=3D"Counting">counting</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tally_marks" title=3D"Tally mark=
s">tally marks</a> used to keep track of quantities. Some historians sugges=
t that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebombo_bone" title=3D"=
Lebombo bone">Lebombo bone</a> (dated about 43,000 years ago) and the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ishango_bone" title=3D"Ishango bone">Is=
hango bone</a> (dated about 22,000 to 30,000 years ago) are the oldest arit=
hmetic artifacts but this interpretation is disputed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16=
5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#=
cite_note-165"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>156<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, a basic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Number_sense" title=3D"Number sense">sense of numbers</a> may pr=
edate these findings and might even have existed before the development of =
language.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-166" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-166"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>157<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>It was not until the emergence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Ancient_civilizations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient civili=
zations">ancient civilizations</a> that a more complex and structured appro=
ach to arithmetic began to evolve, starting around 3000 BCE. This became ne=
cessary because of the increased need to keep track of stored items, manage=
 land ownership, and arrange exchanges.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-167" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-167"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>158<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> All the major ancient civilizations developed non-positional =
numeral systems to facilitate the representation of numbers. They also had =
symbols for operations like addition and subtraction and were aware of frac=
tions. Examples are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egyptian_hiero=
glyphics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Egyptian hieroglyphics">Egyptian h=
ieroglyphics</a> as well as the numeral systems invented in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sumeria" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sumeria">=
Sumeria</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_China" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient China">China</a>, and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_India" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient=
 India">India</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-168" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-168"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>159<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The fir=
st <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positional_numeral_system" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positional numeral system">positional numeral sy=
stem</a> was developed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baby=
lonians" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Babylonians">Babylonians</a> starti=
ng around 1800 BCE. This was a significant improvement over earlier numeral=
 systems since it made the representation of large numbers and calculations=
 on them more efficient.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-169" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-169"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>160<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abacus" title=3D"Abacus">Abacuses</=
a> have been utilized as hand-operated calculating tools since ancient time=
s as efficient means for performing complex calculations.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-170" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithme=
tic#cite_note-170"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>161<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Early civilizations primarily used numbers for concrete practical pu=
rposes, like commercial activities and tax records, but lacked an abstract =
concept of number itself.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-171" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-171"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>162<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> This changed with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Gr=
eek_mathematicians" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient Greek mathematic=
ians">ancient Greek mathematicians</a>, who began to explore the abstract n=
ature of numbers rather than studying how they are applied to specific prob=
lems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-172" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-172"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>163<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Another novel featur=
e was their use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_pr=
oof" title=3D"Mathematical proof">proofs</a> to establish mathematical trut=
hs and validate theories.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-173" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-173"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>164<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> A further contribution was their distinction of various classes of number=
s, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Even_numbers" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Even numbers">even numbers</a>, odd numbers, and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Prime numbers">prime numbers</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-174" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-17=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>165<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> This included the discovery that numbers for certain geomet=
rical lengths are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_numbe=
r" title=3D"Irrational number">irrational</a> and therefore cannot be expre=
ssed as a fraction.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-175" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-175"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The wo=
rks of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thales_of_Miletus" title=3D=
"Thales of Miletus">Thales of Miletus</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Pythagoras" title=3D"Pythagoras">Pythagoras</a> in the 7th and =
6th centuries BCE are often regarded as the inception of Greek mathematics.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-176" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-176"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Diophantus" title=3D"Diophantus">Diophantus</a> was an infl=
uential figure in Greek arithmetic in the 3rd century CE because of his num=
erous contributions to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theo=
ry" title=3D"Number theory">number theory</a> and his exploration of the ap=
plication of arithmetic operations to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Algebraic_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Algebraic equations=
">algebraic equations</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-177" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-177"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>168<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>The ancient Indians were the first to develop the concept of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Zero=
">zero</a> as a number to be used in calculations. The exact rules of its o=
peration were written down by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brah=
magupta" title=3D"Brahmagupta">Brahmagupta</a> in around 628 CE.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-178" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Arithmetic#cite_note-178"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>169<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The concept of zero or none existed =
long before, but it was not considered an object of arithmetic operations.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-179" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-179"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17=
0<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Brahmagupta further provid=
ed a detailed discussion of calculations with <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Negative_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Negative numbe=
rs">negative numbers</a> and their application to problems like credit and =
debt.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-180" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-180"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>171<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The concept of negat=
ive numbers itself is significantly older and was <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/The_Nine_Chapters_on_the_Mathematical_Art" title=3D"The Nin=
e Chapters on the Mathematical Art">first explored</a> in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_mathematics" title=3D"Chinese mathematics">=
Chinese mathematics</a> in the first millennium BCE.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-181=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#c=
ite_note-181"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>172<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Indian mathematicians also developed the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Hindu%E2%80%93Arabic_numeral_system" title=3D"Hindu=E2=80=93A=
rabic numeral system">positional decimal</a> system used today, in particul=
ar the concept of a zero digit instead of empty or missing positions.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-182" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-182"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>173<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aryabhatiya" title=3D"Aryabhatiya">a detailed treatm=
ent</a> of its operations was provided by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Aryabhata" title=3D"Aryabhata">Aryabhata</a> around the turn of the=
 6th century CE.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-183" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-183"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>174<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The India=
n decimal system was further refined and expanded to non-integers during th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamic_Golden_Age" title=3D"Isl=
amic Golden Age">Islamic Golden Age</a> by Middle Eastern mathematicians, s=
uch as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Khwarizmi" title=3D"Al-K=
hwarizmi">Al-Khwarizmi</a>. His work was influential in introducing the dec=
imal numeral system to the Western world, which at that time relied on the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_numeral_system" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Roman numeral system">Roman numeral system</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-184" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Arithmetic#cite_note-184"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>175<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There, it was popularized by mat=
hematicians like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonardo_Fibonacc=
i" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Leonardo Fibonacci">Leonardo Fibonacci</a=
>, who lived in the 12th and 13th centuries and also developed the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_sequence" title=3D"Fibonacci se=
quence">Fibonacci sequence</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-185" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-185"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>176<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> During the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Ages" titl=
e=3D"Middle Ages">Middle Ages</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Renaissance" title=3D"Renaissance">Renaissance</a>, many popular textbo=
oks were published to cover the practical calculations for commerce. The us=
e of abacuses also became widespread in this period.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-186=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#c=
ite_note-186"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>177<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> In the 16th century, the mathematician <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerolamo_Cardano" title=3D"Gerolamo Carda=
no">Gerolamo Cardano</a> conceived the concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Complex_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Complex num=
bers">complex numbers</a> as a way to solve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Cubic_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cubic equations">=
cubic equations</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-187" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-187"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>178<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Leibniz_Stepped_Reckoner.png" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-description"><img alt=3D"Photo of Leibniz's stepped reckoner" src=3D"http=
s://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Leibniz_Stepped_Recko=
ner.png/250px-Leibniz_Stepped_Reckoner.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250=
" height=3D"163" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1235" data-fi=
le-height=3D"803"></a><figcaption>Leibniz's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Stepped_reckoner" title=3D"Stepped reckoner">stepped reckoner</a>=
 was the first calculator that could perform all four arithmetic operations=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-188" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-188"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
179<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>The first <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanical_calculator=
" title=3D"Mechanical calculator">mechanical calculators</a> were developed=
 in the 17th century and greatly facilitated complex mathematical calculati=
ons, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaise_Pascal" title=
=3D"Blaise Pascal">Blaise Pascal</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Pascal%27s_calculator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pascal's calcula=
tor">calculator</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_=
Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leib=
niz</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stepped_reckoner" title=
=3D"Stepped reckoner">stepped reckoner</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-189" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_not=
e-189"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>180<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> The 17th century also saw the discovery of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithm<=
/a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Napier" title=3D"John =
Napier">John Napier</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-190" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-190"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>181<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 18th and 19th centuries, mathematicians such as <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonha=
rd Euler</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Ga=
uss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a> laid the found=
ations of modern number theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-191" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-191"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>182<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Another development in this period concerned work on the formalizatio=
n and foundations of arithmetic, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Georg_Cantor" title=3D"Georg Cantor">Georg Cantor</a>'s <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory" title=3D"Set theory">set theory</a=
> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dedekind%E2%80%93Peano_a=
xioms" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dedekind=E2=80=93Peano axioms">Dedeki=
nd=E2=80=93Peano axioms</a> used as an axiomatization of natural-number ari=
thmetic.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-192" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-192"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>183<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Computers=
">Computers</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_cal=
culators" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electronic calculators">electronic=
 calculators</a> were first developed in the 20th century. Their widespread=
 use revolutionized both the accuracy and speed with which even complex ari=
thmetic computations can be calculated.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-193" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-193"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>184<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_various_fields">In vario=
us fields</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DAr=
ithmetic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: In vari=
ous fields"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Education">Education</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Education"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_educatio=
n" title=3D"Mathematics education">Mathematics education</a></div>
<p>Arithmetic education forms part of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Primary_education" title=3D"Primary education">primary education</a>. I=
t is one of the first forms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mat=
hematics_education" title=3D"Mathematics education">mathematics education</=
a> that children encounter. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elemen=
tary_arithmetic" title=3D"Elementary arithmetic">Elementary arithmetic</a> =
aims to give students a basic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numb=
er_sense" title=3D"Number sense">sense of numbers</a> and to familiarize th=
em with fundamental numerical operations like addition, subtraction, multip=
lication, and division.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-194" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-194"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>185<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It=
 is usually introduced in relation to concrete scenarios, like counting <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bead" title=3D"Bead">beads</a>, divid=
ing the class into groups of children of the same size, and calculating cha=
nge when buying items. Common tools in early arithmetic education are <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_lines" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Number lines">number lines</a>, addition and multiplication tables, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counting_blocks" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Counting blocks">counting blocks</a>, and abacuses.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-195" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Arithmetic#cite_note-195"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>186<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Later stages focus on a more abstract understanding and introduce th=
e students to different types of numbers, such as negative numbers, fractio=
ns, real numbers, and complex numbers. They further cover more advanced num=
erical operations, like exponentiation, extraction of roots, and logarithm.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-196" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-196"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> They also show how arithm=
etic operations are employed in other branches of mathematics, such as thei=
r application to describe geometrical shapes and the use of variables in al=
gebra. Another aspect is to teach the students the use of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithms</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculator" title=3D"Calculator">ca=
lculators</a> to solve complex arithmetic problems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-197"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#ci=
te_note-197"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>188<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Psychology">Psychology</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: Psychology"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychology" title=3D"Psycho=
logy">psychology</a> of arithmetic is interested in how humans and animals =
learn about numbers, represent them, and use them for calculations. It exam=
ines how mathematical problems are understood and solved and how arithmetic=
 abilities are related to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percepti=
on" title=3D"Perception">perception</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Memory" title=3D"Memory">memory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Judgment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Judgment">judgment</a>, =
and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_making" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Decision making">decision making</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
198" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmeti=
c#cite_note-198"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>189<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, it investigates how collections =
of concrete items are first encountered in perception and subsequently asso=
ciated with numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-199" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-199"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>190<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A fur=
ther field of inquiry concerns the relation between numerical calculations =
and the use of language to form representations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-200" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_=
note-200"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>191<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Psychology also explores the biological origin of ar=
ithmetic as an inborn ability. This concerns pre-verbal and pre-symbolic co=
gnitive processes implementing arithmetic-like operations required to succe=
ssfully represent the world and perform tasks like spatial navigation.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-201" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-201"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>192<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>One of the concepts studied by psychology is <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Numeracy" title=3D"Numeracy">numeracy</a>, which is the c=
apability to comprehend numerical concepts, apply them to concrete situatio=
ns, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_reasoning" title=
=3D"Logical reasoning">reason</a> with them. It includes a fundamental numb=
er sense as well as being able to estimate and compare quantities. It furth=
er encompasses the abilities to symbolically represent numbers in numbering=
 systems, interpret <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_data=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Numerical data">numerical data</a>, and ev=
aluate arithmetic calculations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-202" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-202"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>193<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Numeracy is a key skill in many academic fields. A lack of numeracy c=
an inhibit academic success and lead to bad economic decisions in everyday =
life, for example, by misunderstanding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Mortgage" title=3D"Mortgage">mortgage</a> plans and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insurance_policies" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"I=
nsurance policies">insurance policies</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-203" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-2=
03"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>194<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Philosophy">Philosophy</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: Philosophy"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy_of_mathem=
atics" title=3D"Philosophy of mathematics">Philosophy of mathematics</a></d=
iv>
<p>The philosophy of arithmetic studies the fundamental concepts and princi=
ples underlying numbers and arithmetic operations. It explores the nature a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontology" title=3D"Ontology">on=
tological status</a> of numbers, the relation of arithmetic to language and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic" title=3D"Logic">logic</a>,=
 and how it is possible to acquire arithmetic <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Knowledge" title=3D"Knowledge">knowledge</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-204" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithme=
tic#cite_note-204"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>195<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platonism" tit=
le=3D"Platonism">Platonism</a>, numbers have mind-independent existence: th=
ey exist as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_objects" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Abstract objects">abstract objects</a> outside s=
pacetime and without causal powers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-205" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-205"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>196<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-207" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-207"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>j<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This view is rejec=
ted by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intuitionism" title=3D"Intu=
itionism">intuitionists</a>, who claim that mathematical objects are mental=
 constructions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-208" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-208"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>198<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Further th=
eories are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logicism" title=3D"Logi=
cism">logicism</a>, which holds that mathematical truths are reducible to <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_truth" title=3D"Logical tru=
th">logical truths</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-209" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-209"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>199<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formalism_(philosophy_of_mathema=
tics)" title=3D"Formalism (philosophy of mathematics)">formalism</a>, which=
 states that mathematical principles are rules of how symbols are manipulat=
ed without claiming that they correspond to entities outside the rule-gover=
ned activity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-210" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-210"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>200<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The traditionally dominant view in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Epistemology" title=3D"Epistemology">epistemology</a> of arithm=
etic is that arithmetic truths are knowable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/A_priori" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"A priori">a priori</a>. =
This means that they can be known by thinking alone without the need to rel=
y on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensory_experience" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Sensory experience">sensory experience</a>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-211" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Arithmetic#cite_note-211"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>201<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some proponents of this view state =
that arithmetic knowledge is innate while others claim that there is some f=
orm of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_intuition" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rational intuition">rational intuition</a> throug=
h which mathematical truths can be apprehended.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-212" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_n=
ote-212"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>202<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> A more recent alternative view was suggested by <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naturalism_(philosophy)" title=3D"Natur=
alism (philosophy)">naturalist</a> philosophers like <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Willard_Van_Orman_Quine" title=3D"Willard Van Orman Quin=
e">Willard Van Orman Quine</a>, who argue that mathematical principles are =
high-level generalizations that are ultimately grounded in the sensory worl=
d as described by the empirical sciences.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-213" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-21=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>203<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Others_2">Others</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DArithmetic&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Others"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Arithmetic is relevant to many fields. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Daily_life" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Daily life">daily lif=
e</a>, it is required to calculate change when shopping, manage <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Personal_finances" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Personal finances">personal finances</a>, and adjust a cooking recipe =
for a different number of servings. Businesses use arithmetic to calculate =
profits and losses and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marketing_r=
esearch" title=3D"Marketing research">analyze market trends</a>. In the fie=
ld of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engine=
ering">engineering</a>, it is used to measure quantities, calculate loads a=
nd forces, and design structures.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-214" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-214"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>204<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptography" title=3D"Cry=
ptography">Cryptography</a> relies on arithmetic operations to protect sens=
itive information by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encrypt" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Encrypt">encrypting</a> data and messages.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-215" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-215"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>205<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Arithmetic is intimately connected to many branches of mathematics t=
hat depend on numerical operations. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">Algebra</a> relies on arithmetic principles to=
 solve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equation" title=3D"Equation=
">equations</a> using variables. These principles also play a key role in <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calcul=
us</a> in its attempt to determine <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Rates_of_change" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rates of change">rates of =
change</a> and areas under <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve" =
title=3D"Curve">curves</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geomet=
ry" title=3D"Geometry">Geometry</a> uses arithmetic operations to measure t=
he properties of shapes while <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stat=
istics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a> utilizes them to analyze numeri=
cal data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-216" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-216"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>206<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Due to the relev=
ance of arithmetic operations throughout mathematics, the influence of arit=
hmetic extends to most sciences such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer science">computer science</=
a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Econom=
ics">economics</a>. These operations are used in calculations, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem-solving" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Problem-solving">problem-solving</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Data_analysis" title=3D"Data analysis">data analysis</a>, and algor=
ithms, making them integral to scientific research, technological developme=
nt, and economic modeling.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-217" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic#cite_note-217"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>207<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
